Hass Avocado Analysis

This dataset was pulled from: https://www.kaggle.com/neuromusic/avocado-prices/home

It contains historical data on avocado prices and sales volume in a variety of US markets.

Some questions I want to look at in this analysis:

  • What happened to avocado prices and consumption in 2017?
  • How do the prices of avocados vary by region?

Load and Examine Dataset

Variable descriptions are provided by the dataset poster:

  • Date - The date of the observation
  • AveragePrice - the average price of a single avocado
  • type - conventional or organic
  • year - the year
  • Region - the city or region of the observation
  • Total Volume - Total number of avocados sold
  • 4046 - Total number of avocados with PLU 4046 sold / small hass avocados
  • 4225 - Total number of avocados with PLU 4225 sold / large hass avocados
  • 4770 - Total number of avocados with PLU 4770 sold / x-large hass avocados

After some exploration, I realized that it didnt make sense to chart organic and conventional avocados together as their sales numbers are orders of magnitude apart. I broke up the dataset by region in order to create graphs that made sense. What happened to avocado prices and consumption in 2017?

We can see in the chart above that the median price of organic avocados is ~50 cents higher than conventional avocados. The price distributions for both organic and conventional avocados are normally distributed.

People choose to buy organic avocados over conventional for a variety of reasons, but some of the reasons contribute to an increase in prices. There is typically a higher production cost associated with organic foods and the production and distribution chains are not nearly as robust. For these reasons and more, we should expect that the organic avocados are in general more expensive.

Now lets take a look at the average avocado price over time and see if there are any trends.

We can see in these graphs that there is a cyclical trend that has emerged for the price of avocados regardless of type. The average price of avocados dip around the new year and are most expensive during the summer. This also corresponds to a yearly increase in avocado consumption around the new year.

Additionally, we can see that the total volume of conventional avocado sales has remained relatively level but there is a steady increase in average organic avocado sales. Even with the increase in organic avocado sales, the conventional avocado sales volume still dwarfs that of the organic variety.

Outside of the continuing increase in organic avocado sales, it does not appear that the price or consumption of avocados in general changed notably during 2017.

How do the prices of avocados vary by region?

Reported statistics say that the majority of avocados consumed in the U.S. are produced either in Mexico or California. Based on that information, I would expect that regions along the southern and western US borders have the lowest distribution costs and therefore lower prices.

Here we can see the distribution costs reflected in the average price by region. The South-Central, West, and and South-East regions have the lowest average price whereas the North-East and New England regions have the highest. I would also guess that avocado availability is less sensitive to the seasonal changes in the south and west. This combined with the price discrepancy probably contributes significantly to these regions high average sales volumes.
